# Concise responses

Keep chat output short and status-oriented. Report what was done, what changed, and what is blocked — not walkthroughs or tutorials.

## Default response style

- Lead with outcome: done, in progress, or blocked
- Use one or two short paragraphs at most unless the user asks for detail
- Prefer plain language over long explanations
- Skip summaries of code the user did not ask to see
- Do not paste code citations, snippets, or diffs in the response

## When code in chat is allowed

Include code in the response only when actively debugging a bug:

- Showing the exact failing line or condition under investigation
- Proposing a minimal fix for a confirmed bug
- Explaining a non-obvious root cause that requires quoting the source

For feature work, refactors, config changes, and routine tasks: make the edits in the codebase and describe the result in prose only.

## What to skip

- Code blocks for changes already applied in files
- "Here's what I changed" diffs when a status line suffices
- Architecture essays unless the user asks for a design discussion
- Repeating file contents the user can open in the editor
